<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
Body flattened. Five arms that taper gradually towards their extremities (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Some species of the family Luidiidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Luidia ludwigi scotti (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail abactinal intermediate area B Actinal view, in detail the mouth C Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla D Actinal view. Luidia senegalensis (E-H) E Abactinal view F Actinal view, in detail the mouth G Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">4a, b</figureCitation>
). Abactinal surface with paxillae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Some species of the family Luidiidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Luidia ludwigi scotti (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail abactinal intermediate area B Actinal view, in detail the mouth C Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla D Actinal view. Luidia senegalensis (E-H) E Abactinal view F Actinal view, in detail the mouth G Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">4a</figureCitation>
). Dorsal paxillae small, ordered, with 1-6 central, short, blunt spinelets, and 18 marginal, slender, and denticulate spinelets (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Some species of the family Luidiidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Luidia ludwigi scotti (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail abactinal intermediate area B Actinal view, in detail the mouth C Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla D Actinal view. Luidia senegalensis (E-H) E Abactinal view F Actinal view, in detail the mouth G Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">4c</figureCitation>
). Adradial paxillae rectangular or quadrangular, slightly larger than the carinal paxillae. Inferomarginal figs with one pointed, elongate spine (~2.04 mm) forming the marginal fringe (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Some species of the family Luidiidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Luidia ludwigi scotti (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail abactinal intermediate area B Actinal view, in detail the mouth C Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla D Actinal view. Luidia senegalensis (E-H) E Abactinal view F Actinal view, in detail the mouth G Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">4a</figureCitation>
). The remaining part of the fig is covered by short, hyaline and denticulate spinelets. Actinal surface with inferomarginal figs, densely covered by flattened and lanceolate spines (Fig. b, d). Actinolateral fig with three short, slender, divergent spines. The median of these is the largest. The ambulacral spine long, flattened and slender (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Some species of the family Luidiidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Luidia ludwigi scotti (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail abactinal intermediate area B Actinal view, in detail the mouth C Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla D Actinal view. Luidia senegalensis (E-H) E Abactinal view F Actinal view, in detail the mouth G Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">4d</figureCitation>
). Bivalved pedicellariae present only on the actinal surface, mainly on the ventro-lateral figs and in the areas close to the arms, never occurring on the abactinal surface. Oral spines slender, long (~1.18 mm) with blunt tip, forming a bundle of spines at apex of jaw (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Some species of the family Luidiidae recorded in northeastern Brazil. Luidia ludwigi scotti (A-D) A Abactinal view, in detail abactinal intermediate area B Actinal view, in detail the mouth C Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla D Actinal view. Luidia senegalensis (E-H) E Abactinal view F Actinal view, in detail the mouth G Abactinal view of the arm, in detail the paxilla, and H Actinal view of the arm." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">4c</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
