, 
<bibRefCitation author="Tommasi, LR" journalOrPublisher="Anales del Instituto de Biologia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 61" refId="B134" refString="Tommasi, LR, 1970. Lista de asteroides recentes do Brasil. In: Contribuicoes do Instituto Oceanografico, Universidade de Sao Paulo.: 1 - 61" title="Lista de asteroides recentes do Brasil." volumeTitle="Contribuicoes do Instituto Oceanografico, Universidade de Sao Paulo." year="1970">Tommasi 1970</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey 1992</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Benavides-Serrato, M" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="171 - 194" refId="B11" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M, Borrero-Perez, GH, Solano, OD, Navas, GR, 2005. Listado taxonomico de los asteroideos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) de la plataforma y talud superior del Caribe colombiano. Revista de Biologia Tropical 53: 171 - 194" title="Listado taxonomico de los asteroideos (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) de la plataforma y talud superior del Caribe colombiano." volume="53" year="2005">Benavides-Serrato et al. 2005</bibRefCitation>
). In Brazil: RJ, SP, and SC (
<bibRefCitation author="Brito, IM" journalOrPublisher="Universidade do Brasil, Faculdade Nacional de Filosofia, Centro de Estudos Zoologicos" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 10" refId="B21" refString="Brito, IM, 1962. Ensaio de catalogo dos equinodermas do Brasil. Universidade do Brasil, Faculdade Nacional de Filosofia, Centro de Estudos Zoologicos: 1 - 10" title="Ensaio de catalogo dos equinodermas do Brasil" year="1962">Brito 1962</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Brito, IM" journalOrPublisher="Universidade do Brasil, Faculdade Nacional de Filosofia, Centro de Estudos Zoologicos" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 51" refId="B22" refString="Brito, IM, 1968. Asteroides e equinoides do Estado da Guanabara e adjacencias. In: Boletim do Museu Nacional.: 1 - 51" title="Asteroides e equinoides do Estado da Guanabara e adjacencias." volumeTitle="Boletim do Museu Nacional." year="1968">1968</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Xavier, LAR" journalOrPublisher="Brazilian Journal of Aquatic Science and Technology" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="73 - 78" publicationUrl="10.14210/bjast.v14n2.p73-78" refId="B157" refString="Xavier, LAR, 2010. Inventario dos equinodermos do Estado de Santa Catarina, Brasil. Brazilian Journal of Aquatic Science and Technology 14: 73 - 78, DOI: 10.14210/bjast.v14n2.p73-78" title="Inventario dos equinodermos do Estado de Santa Catarina, Brasil." url="10.14210/bjast.v14n2.p73-78" volume="14" year="2010">Xavier 2010</bibRefCitation>
). This is the first record of the species for the littoral of northeast Brazil. From 20 to 126 m in depth. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey (1992)</bibRefCitation>
considered the previous record at 5 m for the State of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Paulo to be doubtful. Thus the present study expands the bathymetric distribution to 20 m deep, previously established at 33-126 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
This subspecies may be distinguished from other taxa in the genus by the presence of pedicellariae with three or four well-developed valves on the actinal surface, the delicate structure of the paxillae, and the slightly triangular shape of the arms, which become narrow distally. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Say" baseAuthorityYear="1825" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia clathrata" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="clathrata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia clathrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1917" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia ludwigi subsp. scotti" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="ludwigi" subSpecies="scotti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia ludwigi scotti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but may be distinguished from it by having a stronger actinal skeleton and by the absence of pedicellariae. The synonymy between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="John &amp; Clark" authorityYear="1954" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia rosaurae" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="rosaurae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia rosaurae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
John &amp; Clark, 1954 and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1917" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia scotti" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="scotti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia scotti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was proposed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum, Natural History" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="157 - 184" refId="B32" refString="Clark, AM, 1982. Notes on Atlantic Asteroidea 2. Luidiidae. Bulletin of the British Museum, Natural History 42: 157 - 184" title="Notes on Atlantic Asteroidea 2. Luidiidae." volume="42" year="1982">Clark (1982)</bibRefCitation>
, who observed that the differences in the inferomarginal spines previously established between the two species were insignificant and unable to support the independence of the two species. Furthermore, with the observations of 
<bibRefCitation author="Walenkamp, JHC" journalOrPublisher="Zoologische Verhandelingen" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="1 - 91" refId="B153" refString="Walenkamp, JHC, 1976. The asteroids of the coastal waters of Surinam. Zoologische Verhandelingen 147: 1 - 91" title="The asteroids of the coastal waters of Surinam." volume="147" year="1976">Walenkamp (1976)</bibRefCitation>
that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="John &amp; Clark" authorityYear="1954" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia rosaurae" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="rosaurae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia rosaurae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1906" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia ludwigi" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="ludwigi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia ludwigi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fisher, 1906, 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey (1992)</bibRefCitation>
recognized the subspecies 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1917" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia ludwigi subsp. scotti" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="ludwigi" subSpecies="scotti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia ludwigi scotti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for specimens from the Atlantic, as these have a paxillar arrangement that is distinct from the remaining species previously cited. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, AM" journalOrPublisher="Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="B33" refString="Clark, AM, Downey, ME, 1992. Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, UK" title="Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall Identification Guides, 3." year="1992">Clark and Downey (1992)</bibRefCitation>
, the relationships between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bernasconi" authorityYear="1941" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia patriae" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="patriae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia patriae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bernasconi, 1941 and this subspecies still need to be investigated. The specimen analised in this study, even though representing a juvenile individual, did not present significant morphological variations when compared with the characters described for adult specimens, indicating that the morphological characters of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1917" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia ludwigi subsp. scotti" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="ludwigi" subSpecies="scotti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia ludwigi scotti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
do not vary significantly during ontogeny.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="ecological notes">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Ecological notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
This subspecies occurs in non-consolidated sediments containing fine or coarse sand (
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, ABM" journalOrPublisher="Livro vermelho da fauna brasileira ameacada de extincao. (Serie Biodiversidade 19)" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" refId="B81" refString="Machado, ABM, Drummond, GM, Paglia, AP, 2008. . Livro vermelho da fauna brasileira ameacada de extincao. (Serie Biodiversidade 19) Vol. I" volume="Vol. I" year="2008">Machado et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
). In contrast to other taxa of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1839" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which do not present prey selectivity, in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1917" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia ludwigi subsp. scotti" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="ludwigi" subSpecies="scotti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia ludwigi scotti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only eight different food types have been recorded, of which bivalves, foraminiferans and ophiuroids are their main prey (
<bibRefCitation author="Benavides-Serrato, M" journalOrPublisher="Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" refId="B12" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M, Borrero-Perez, GH, Dias Sanchez, CM, 2011. Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea. Serie de Publicaciones Especiales de Invemar, 22. Santa Marta" title="Equinodermos del Caribe colombiano I: Crinoidea, Asteroidea y Ophiuroidea." year="2011">Benavides-Serrato et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
). The presence of different prey species of distinct sizes in the stomachs of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell" authorityYear="1917" class="Asteroidea" family="Luidiidae" genus="Luidia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Luidia ludwigi subsp. scotti" order="Paxillosida" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="ludwigi" subSpecies="scotti">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Luidia ludwigi scotti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
probably reflects a response to competition and coexistence with other species of sea-stars (
<bibRefCitation author="Broegger, MI" journalOrPublisher="Revista de Biologia Tropical" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="329 - 334" refId="B24" refString="Broegger, MI, Penchaszadeh, PE, 2008. Infaunal mollusks as main prey for two sand bottoms sea stars off Puerto Quequen (Argentina). Revista de Biologia Tropical 56: 329 - 334" title="Infaunal mollusks as main prey for two sand bottoms sea stars off Puerto Quequen (Argentina)." volume="56" year="2008">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Brögger">Broegger</normalizedToken>
and Penchaszadeh 2008
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
